<br>
In fact, boys and girls, &quot;bias free reporting&quot; is actually a relatively new phenomenon in journalism, dating back to the Civil War.  Publishers used this approach because it allowed them to sell papers on both sides of the Mason-Dixon.  It was a purely financial move, it wasn't based in altruism, or a dedication to the truth.<br>
<br>
2) Mistakes are made in Live television.  I'm going to assume that none of you have been in a control room during a breaking news situation, so I will explain what happens:  The producer speaks in to the anchor's IFB (earpiece to you laypeople), people hand the anchor scripts and scraps of paper, the teleprompter gets updated, and the floor people use hand signals.<br>
<br>
In a live situation, anchors have been known to misspeak, misinterpret, or mishear information while tap dancing and explaining what's happening.  The producer has been often known to mishear, misinterpret, or misspeak something to the anchor, in the heat of the moment.<br>
<br>
The official on the scene has been known to do the exact same thing.<br>
<br>
In order to give the viewer the absolute latest on a breaking news event, a lot of things have to happen.  Dozens of people are involved at the very minimum.<br>
<br>
So, when a bitter print journalist sits in his solitary windowless room and Monday Morning quarterbacks live coverage, it's pretty easy to set himself on a high horse.<br>
 <br>
                                                 xxoo,<br>
<br>
                                          Lowfyr Wildforge<br>
<br>
<br>
P.S. Yep, I worked in television news.<br>
